# Plugin Development Rules

This repository contains an OpsRabbit plugin generated from `{{starterId}}` with
CLI version `{{cliVersion}}` and SDK range `{{sdkVersion}}`.

## Required boundaries

- Import only public exports from `@opsrabbit/plugin-sdk`.
- Treat tenant ids, actor ids, record ids, and secret references as opaque values.
- Declare every capability used by registered tools, actions, routes, widgets,
  jobs, or tenant-record storage.
- Keep `opsrabbit.plugin.json` authoritative. Do not duplicate identity, version,
  or capability declarations in runtime source.
- Never bypass host authorization, capability brokers, audit, cancellation, or
  resource limits.
- Never embed credentials, database URLs, internal OpsRabbit endpoints, or
  product source.
- Keep every operation tenant-scoped. Do not cache data across invocation or
  tenant boundaries.
- Validate untrusted input and avoid logging secrets or full sensitive payloads.
- Database plugins use the host-provided tenant-record API only. They do not run
  arbitrary SQL or receive database credentials.

## Quality gates

Before proposing a release, run `npm run check`, `npm run test:coverage`,
`npm run build`, `npm run plugin:check`, and `npm run plugin:pack`. Add meaningful
unit tests for success, authorization-sensitive behavior, invalid input, and
failure paths. Keep manifest and package versions identical.

Release only from a reviewed commit on `main`. The generated workflow preserves
an explicit unreleased version or automatically increments the released patch
version, then creates an immutable matching `vX.Y.Z` tag. It owns ZIP, checksum,
SPDX SBOM, optional provenance attestation, and GitHub Release creation. Never
replace an existing tag or hand-edit generated release assets. Upload only the
named plugin ZIP asset, never GitHub's automatic source-code archive.

